               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18720226-name-253" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-253" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-253" type="surname" value="PIERPOINT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-253" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL PIERPOINT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am porter to Messrs. Statham and Son, wholesale watch manufacturers, of 12, Old Jewry Chambers—on 4th January I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187202260050"></xptr>
               <p>received a parcel at 12, Old Jewry Chambers, from Mr. Jepson one of our travellers—it was addressed "W. Burnet, Durham"—I took it to the Cross Keys, paid for the booking, and delivered it to Duperry, at 6 o'clock—I did not see the watch.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18720226-name-254" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-254" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-254" type="surname" value="DUPERRY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-254" type="given" value="JAMES THOMAS"></interp>JAMES THOMAS DUPERRY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am receiving clerk at the Cross Keys, in the employ of Chaplin and Horne—on 4th January, at a little before 6 o'clock, I received from Pierpoint a parcel addressed to Mr. Burnet, of Durham—I entered it on the way bill and gave it into the Charge of Rope, the con<lb></lb>ductor of the omnibus which carries parcels from the Cross Keys to Euston Square Station.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18720226-name-255" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-255" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-255" type="surname" value="ROPE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-255" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE ROPE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am omnibus conductor, No. 2, 203, and am in the service of Chaplin and Horne—on 4th January, shortly after 6 o'clock, I received from Duperry a certain number of parcels, among which was one addressed to Mr. Burnet, of Durham.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18720226-name-256" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-256" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-256" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-256" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY JONES</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a clerk in the London and North Western Railway parcels office, Euston Square—it is my duty to receive parcels and check each off, according to the items in the way bill—I found that a parcel addressed to Mr. Burnet, of Durham, was missing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18720226-name-257" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-257" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-257" type="surname" value="PUCHEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-257" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES PUCHEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Statham and Son, Old Jewry Chambers—on 4th January I delivered a watch in a packet to Pierpoint, I believe, addressed to Mr. Burnet of Durham; this is it (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) it is worth 32<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. trade price.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18720226-name-258" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-258" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-258" type="surname" value="GOULD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-258" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>DAVID GOULD</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep a lodging-house at 9, Market Street, Fitzroy Square—Thomas lodged there three or four weeks, and Adams three or four months previous to 4th January—I never noticed previous to 5th January that they were acquainted with one another—on the night of January 4th Thomas asked me to take charge of this watch till next morning—he said that he had been over to his brother at Blackheath, but did not see him; that his brother had lent him 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. on that watch some time ago, and he saw his wife, who gave him back the watch, and told him he could pay the 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. when he got into work again—I put it into my desk, and delivered it to him next morning—Adams followed him out—on the 7th Thomas left with me this duplicate of a watch pawned for 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—they had both slept there on the 5th and 6th—they have never been back since the 7th.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I believed the story Thomas told me about the watch—he gave me the watch as security for his lodging, and I believed it had been honestly come by—there is no reason why Adams should not have believed the same.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18720226-name-259" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-259" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-259" type="surname" value="BURNET"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18720226-name-259" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES BURNET</persName>
                  </hi>. I am manager to Mr. Griffiths, a pawnbroker of Ossulston Street—the watch was pledged there on 5th January for 25<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. by Adams.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> It is not unusual for persons to pledge in the name of Smith, or Williams, or any other name.</p>
